WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.360
So I'm going to give an update on some of the current strategies we are deploying in

00:00:06.360 --> 00:00:13.380
treatment of CCUS that includes mostly a lot of investigator-initiated studies with

00:00:13.380 --> 00:00:14.600
lisparicept and others.

00:00:14.760 --> 00:00:16.060
These are my disclosures.

00:00:18.120 --> 00:00:24.900
To just go over, you know, the clinical definition of CCUS means you have to have a WHO-defined

00:00:24.900 --> 00:00:28.200
myeloid mutation with a VAF more than 2%.

00:00:28.200 --> 00:00:37.320
The presence of cytopenias and the absence of or defining dysplasia for MDS.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:43.460
CHIP progression is 1% per year, but CCUS progression is about 70% to 80% over a decade.

00:00:44.240 --> 00:00:52.320
So the concept of early intervention in CCUS is stemming from two major goals.

00:00:52.320 --> 00:00:57.220
One is improvement of clinically significant cytopenias.

00:00:57.420 --> 00:00:59.200
And second is prevention of progression.

00:00:59.760 --> 00:01:04.240
And as long as we are trying to get one of these two goals in the right patient population,

00:01:05.180 --> 00:01:06.780
that would be okay.

00:01:07.280 --> 00:01:12.940
Now, you know, this is known that clonal hematopoiesis is associated not just, and this is true for

00:01:12.940 --> 00:01:18.320
CCUS as well, not just for a progression risk to myeloid malignancies, but a syndromic association

00:01:18.320 --> 00:01:26.080
with a lot of inflammatory biological processes that are related to the presence of these mutations

00:01:26.080 --> 00:01:27.220
other than a decreased risk of myeloid malignancies.

00:01:27.220 --> 00:01:27.360
So this is known that clonal hematopoiesis is associated not just, and this is true for CCUS as well, not just for a progression risk to myeloid malignancies, but a syndromic association with a lot of inflammatory biological processes that are related to the presence of these mutations other than a decreased risk of myeloid malignancies.

00:01:27.360 --> 00:01:27.660
So this is known that clonal hematopoiesis is associated not just, and this is true for CCUS as well, not just, and this is true for CCUS as well, not just, and this is true for CCUS as well, not just, and this is true for CCUS as well, not just, and this is true for CCUS as well, not just, and this is true for CCUS as well, not just, and this is true for CCUS as well, not just, and this is true for CCUS as well, not just, and this is true for CCUS as well, not just, and this is true for CCUS as well, not just, and this is true for CCUS as well, not just, and this is true for CCUS as well, but also for myeloid malignancies.

00:01:35.820 --> 00:02:05.760
So the first question you really ask when you want to treat CCUS is how to risk stratify them, and I'm not going to go into details of all the strategies, but there are three current scores that we use, CHRS, myeloid neoplasm predict, and CCUS progression score, all of them have nuances, different ways that they decided that this is high risk or not, and, you know, briefly, if you sort of compare all of them, you'll see that they're all very similar.

00:02:05.760 --> 00:02:19.580
The way I deal with this is I would really put, just for the sake of it, take a patient and put them into all of these risk scores, and just to make sure that they're not, there's nothing discrepant, but they generally work well.

00:02:19.840 --> 00:02:29.560
You want to pick the right score for the right patient population, like TP53 mutated people probably do better with them and predict and things like that.

00:02:29.840 --> 00:02:35.600
But the goal of these scoring is you do have a way to tell that these patients.

00:02:35.700 --> 00:02:43.440
Are at high risk for progression. So these are the people who are going into these CCUS trials.

00:02:43.640 --> 00:03:03.120
Now, if you think about treatment of CCUS, you know, other than clinically significant cytopenias where there's a logic, obviously, to treat them, and the second sort of goal of progression is based on, okay, what are the mechanisms of progression that you can actually target?

00:03:03.120 --> 00:03:05.640
So inflammation, it's known that inflammation.

00:03:05.640 --> 00:03:10.680
Inflammatory signaling worsens clonal hematopoiesis.

00:03:10.680 --> 00:03:20.180
Many people have done great work with models that if you inhibit inflammation, you decrease the clone size.

00:03:20.180 --> 00:03:22.280
So inflammation is a way to target.

00:03:22.280 --> 00:03:26.560
Aging, we haven't had a holy grail, kombucha juice does not work.

00:03:26.560 --> 00:03:34.620
So we can't really stop aging at this moment, but obviously that's a process that has been a big question.

00:03:34.620 --> 00:03:35.580
Term line predisposition.

00:03:35.580 --> 00:03:41.820
Will will also be important, but again, you cannot really change it and obviously, just like, you know, Dr.

00:03:41.820 --> 00:03:49.080
Behar was saying external pressure and avoiding sort of the pressures that lead to a growth in a clone size.

00:03:49.080 --> 00:03:54.060
So these are all the reason all these places that you can use to to target.

00:03:54.060 --> 00:04:00.180
And here's a list of ongoing trials in CCUS that is going through and I'll go through one of the all of them.

00:04:00.180 --> 00:04:05.520
Canakinumab for high risk CCUS with the primary endpoint for.

00:04:05.520 --> 00:04:06.900
Aggression free survival.

00:04:06.900 --> 00:04:13.440
This is a randomized blinded study, which is currently ongoing.

00:04:13.440 --> 00:04:15.900
Umabarati is the PI.

00:04:15.900 --> 00:04:19.860
This trial is open at Cornell and we are enrolling as well.

00:04:19.860 --> 00:04:28.100
We are also enrolling patients into loose paracept with the goal of improvement in cytopenias.

00:04:28.100 --> 00:04:35.460
The IDH mutated CCUS, there are a couple of trials ongoing led by Kelly Bolton.

00:04:35.460 --> 00:04:36.120
And Dr.

00:04:36.120 --> 00:04:43.380
Chin with again the goal of improvement of cytopenias, ascorbic acid, statins and metformin.

00:04:43.380 --> 00:04:48.060
These are more targeting the the metabolism way.

00:04:48.060 --> 00:04:55.620
So let's see what what I'll focus on some of these trials that we are involved in.

